1 Datatypes and Types
For each of the following SML declarations, what is the type of the value being declared? If one of
the expressions is not well-typed, briefly explain why.
Note: Though you can just plug the expression into the SML/NJ REPL and have it do all the work
for you, remember that we might ask you to solve this kind of problem on an exam. We advise you
to learn how to do it by hand, because you won’t have a REPL on the exam.
Use this datatype to answer the following type questions.
datatype digit = Zero | One | Two | Three | Four
| Five | Six | Seven | Eight | Nine

1 + One
Task 1.2. (1 point)
Five + Two
Task 1.3. (1 point)
fn 0 => Zero
Use the following datatypes to answer the next few type questions.
datatype professor = Steve | Mike
datatype job = Student | Professor of professor | TA of string
Task 1.4. (1 point)
Student
Task 1.5. (1 point)
TA
Task 1.6. (1 point)
fun promote (x : job) =
case x of
Student => TA "Polly"
| TA y => Professor y
| z => z
Use the following datatype to answer the next few type questions.
datatype tritree = Empty | Node of int * tritree * tritree * tritree
The int option type is comprised of two constructors: NONE and SOME x, where we have
x : int.
2
Task 1.7. (1 point)
fun numBranches (Node(x, L, M, R)) =
1 + numBranches L + numBranches M + numBranches R
Task 1.8. (1 point)
fun max (Empty : tritree) = NONE
| max (Node (x, L, M, R)) =
let
val currmax = Int.max (Int.max (max L, max M), max R)
in
SOME (Int.max (x, currmax))
end
Note that Int.max : int * int -> int.

2 To the Left, To the Left
Consider the following functions: 1
datatype tree = Empty | Node of tree * int * tree
infixr 5 @
fun [] @ R = R
| (x::xs) @ R = x :: (xs @ R)
fun head ([] : int list) : int option = NONE
| head (x::_) = SOME x
fun inord (Empty : tree) : int list = []
| inord (Node (L,x,R)) = inord L @ x::inord R
fun leftmost (Empty : tree) : int option = NONE
| leftmost (Node (L,x,R)) =
case L of
Empty => SOME x
| Node _ => leftmost L
Task 2.1. (15 points)
Prove that for all values T : tree we have that
leftmost T = head (inord T)
You may also find the following lemmas useful:
Lemma 2.1. For all non- Empty values T : tree, inord T = x::xs for some values x :
int, xs : int list.
Lemma 2.2. @ is total.
Lemma 2.3. inord is total.
Note: As an exercise, try proving this last lemma.
Hint: Consider following the structure of the code!
1 infixr 5 @ defines append (@) as an infix, right-associative function with an operator precedence of 5. Note:
You do not have to worry about what operator precedence 5 means, but if you are curious, it informs us which order
operations are evaluated in an expression.

3 #treedeep5me
We define a subtree inductively as follows:
Definition (Subtree). Let T : tree be a value.
1. T is a subtree of T.
2. Let T’ : tree be a value. If T’ is a subtree of T and T’ = Node (L,x,R), then L
and R are subtrees of T.
As usual, convince yourself that this definition of subtrees is equivalent to the intuitive one.
The lowest common ancestor (lca) between two nodes in a tree is the tree defined by the root
of the smallest subtree that contains both nodes. To further your understanding, consider the
following examples:
4
5
2 0
3
1
•4 is the lowest common ancestor of 2 and 3
•4 is the lowest common ancestor of 1 and 5
•4 is the lowest common ancestor of 1 and 2
•5 is the lowest common ancestor of 0 and 5
•5 is the lowest common ancestor of 0 and 2
•3 is the lowest common ancestor of 1 and 3
In this section, you will be given a tree that does not contain any duplicate values, and two target
values that may or may not be in the tree. Our goal is to implement a function to solve the lca
problem.
It seems costly to repeatedly check whether a value exists in our tree. Our approach will instead use
the path through the tree to each of our target nodes. To achieve this, we introduce the following
datatype:
datatype direction = LEFT | RIGHT
where LEFT indicates traversal through a node’s left subtree, and RIGHT indicates traversal through
a node’s right subtree.

3.1 Testing your code
We know that when we were taking 150, writing test cases for tree functions (wood) keep us up
at night. Thinking about all the nested parentheses would have us recon(cedar)ing whether to test
our code, and we usually ended up (leaf)ing it the way it was.
To write test cases, feel free to use this Tree-to-SML converter:
https://leesue630.github.io/tree-to-sml-converter/
Input the depth, (cy)press ‘Generate SML Text’, and you will(ow) be able to copy-paste the SML
tree into your code.
Note: only the root and nodes with non-empty parents are included in the output.
3.2 Additional hints
For the following tasks, it’s important to make sure that your functions are maximally parallel
so that they have the best possible asymptotic work/span. The primary thing to keep in mind is
that we consider tuples as being evaluated in parallel.
Consider this (somewhat contrived) example:
fun someExpensiveFn (x : int) : int = (* some expensive function *)
val sequential : int =
let
val x = someExpensiveFn 1 (* SML fully evaluates this ... *)
val y = someExpensiveFn 2 (* ... then evaluates this. *)
in
x + y
end
val parallel : int =
let
(* SML evaluates both of these simultaneously *)
val (x,y) = (someExpensiveFn 1, someExpensiveFn 2)
in
x + y
end
(* we pass a tuple to the + function , so doing this is also
maximally parallel *)
val parallel2 : int = (someExpensiveFn 1) + (someExpensiveFn 2)
Be mindful of your order of evaluation when writing your code for the following tasks, and be sure
to optimize things to be more parallel if possible.
6
For each of the following tasks:
•Your code should be maximally parallel.
•Your code shouldn’t need to define any additional helper functions besides the ones you will
implement.
Task 3.1. (2 points)
In code/lca/lca.sml, write the function
find : tree * int -> direction list option
REQUIRES: T contains no duplicates
ENSURES: find (T, v) = NONE if v is not in T, else SOME L, where L is a list of directions
that can be used to traverse from the root of T to v
To clarify the behavior of find, consider the following example:

,0) = SOME [LEFT , RIGHT]

Say that we find a path to one of our target nodes in the tree and produce the direction list L.
If we traverse our input tree according to the directions in any prefix of the list L, we arrive at
an ancestor of our target. Since our goal is to find the lowest common ancestor of our two target
nodes, we want to use the longest prefix that is common to both paths. To achieve this, we will
use two more helper functions.
Task 3.2. (2 points)
In code/lca/lca.sml, write the function
follow : tree * direction list -> tree option
REQUIRES: true
ENSURES: follow (T, L) = NONE if traversing T according to the directions in L do not
lead to a valid subtree of T, else SOME T’, where T’ is the subtree of T that is obtained by
7
traversing T according to L
Task 3.3. (2 points)
In code/lca/lca.sml, write the function
common : direction list * direction list -> direction list
REQUIRES: true
ENSURES: common (L1 , L2) = L, where L is the longest prefix that is common to both
L1 and L2
Constraint:Your implementation of common must have O(min(|L1|, |L2|)) work and span.
Task 3.4. (6 points)
Finally, use find, follow, and common to implement the function
lca : tree * int * int -> tree option
REQUIRES: T contains no duplicates, a <> b
ENSURES: lca (T,a,b) = NONE if a or b are not in T, else SOME (Node (L,x,R))
s.t. Node (L,x,R) is a subtree of T, and either:
•a is in L and b is in R
•b is in L and a is in R
•a = x and b is in L or R
•b = x and a is in L or R
Task 3.5. (8 points)
Write and solve recurrences for the work and span of your implementation of find, follow, and
lca in terms of the number of nodes n in the input tree. For this analysis, assume that the input
tree is balanced. That is, for all subtrees of the form Node (L,x,R), the number of nodes in L
and R differ by at most 1. Please include a copy of your implementation in your written submission,
and show your work when solving for the big-O bounds.
You may assume that common (L1, L2) has O(min(|L1|, |L2|)) work and span. Note: when
indicating the work of common, you should still use Wcommon(k1, k2) where k1, k2 are in
terms of n because we are working with the number of nodes, n.
Constraint: You must use the tree method to solve your recurrences.

4 Compiler Optimizations
In this problem, we will be working with the following datatype, which represents an arithmetic
expression over integers.
datatype exp
= Var of string
| Int of int
| Add of exp * exp
| Mul of exp * exp
| Not of exp
| IfThenElse of exp * exp * exp
Here is the meaning of each constructor in the datatype:
Constructor Meaning
Var x A variable with name x. When evaluating the expression,
this variable must be assigned a value in the environment.
Int n A constant integer with value n.
Add (a,b) The sum of two expressions, a and b.
Mul (a,b) The product of two expressions, a and b.
Not a The “truthy” negation of an integer expression. If a is 0,
Not a should be 1. Otherwise, Not a should be 0.
IfThenElse (i,t,e) “Truthy” casing on integers. If i is nonzero, the expres-
sion evaluates to t. Otherwise, it evaluates to e.
Here are some example representations of operations.
Arithmetic exp
2 + 3 Add (Int 2,Int 3)
2 + x Add (Int 2,Var "x")
3x + 1 Add (Mul (Int 3,Var "x"),Int 1)
3 ·2 + x Add (Mul (Int 3,Int 2),Var "x")
“if x 6= 0 then y else 8” IfThenElse (Var "x",Var "y",Int 8)
“1 if x = 0, else 0” Not (Var "x")
“0 if x = 0, else 1” Not (Not (Var "x"))
Environments We also need a way to represent the “environment”, which contains the variable
bindings. We will use the environ type alias:
type environ = (string * int) list
9
Note that there are three helper functions defined in code/expressions/exp.sml that you might
find useful as you work through the following tasks.
•lookup (env ,x) finds the integer bound to variable x in environment env.
•vars e evaluates to a list of all variable names in expression e.
Full specifications and implementations can be found in the file itself.
4.1 Evaluation
Before we do anything, it would be helpful to define an evaluation function for our datatype. Our
function will take in an environment, which is just a list of string * int pairs representing
which integer each variable name is bound to. You may assume the list has no duplicates.
Task 4.1. (5 points)
In code/expressions/exp.sml, write:
eval : environ * exp -> int
REQUIRES: Each variable in e has one entry in env
ENSURES: eval (env ,e) =⇒∗ n, where n is the integer representing the value of e given
environment env
For example, it should be the case that:
eval ([("x" ,45) ,("y" ,3)],Add (Int 15,Mul (Var "x",Var "y"))) =⇒∗ 150
If you attempt to view deeply-nested exp values, the REPL will stop printing a few layers in,
instead showing a # sign. You can (temporarily) increase the print depth by typing the following
into the REPL:
Control.Print.printDepth := 100
or by running in the terminal:
PRINT_DEPTH =100 ./smlnj exp.sml
4.2 Constant Fusion
Many programming language implementations have optimizations so that the code you write will
run faster. For example, if you write the Python program
def foo(x):
return x + (2 * 3)
an optimization called constant fusion may be applied, transforming the function to
def foo(x):
return x + 6
10
In this case, the constant-fused expression has precomputed (2 * 3), so we can avoid the multi-
plication step at runtime when the function is called. We’ve implemented a similar optimization2 in
code/expressions/fuse.sml that fuses multiplications for our integer expression language:
1 fun fuse (Var x) = Var x
2 | fuse (Int n) = Int n
3 | fuse (Add (a,b)) = Add (fuse a, fuse b)
4 | fuse (Mul (a,b)) = (
5 case (vars a,vars b) of
6 ([] ,[]) => Int (eval ([],a) * eval ([],b))
7 | _ => Mul (fuse a,fuse b)
8 )
9 | fuse (Not a) = Not (fuse a)
10 | fuse (IfThenElse (i,t,e)) = IfThenElse (fuse i,fuse t,fuse e)
11
12 val Add (Var "x",Int 6) = fuse (Add (Var "x", Mul (Int 2,Int 3)))
However, before enabling this optimization, we want to ensure that the constant-fused code is
actually equivalent to the original code. Thankfully, we can prove this fact and sleep soundly for
the rest of our lives.
The next four tasks will refer to the validity of fuse.
Theorem (Validity of fuse). For all values env and e satisfying the REQUIRES for eval,
eval (env ,fuse e) = eval (env ,e)
.
You may make use of the following lemmas:
Lemma 4.1 (Totality of vars). The vars function is total.
Lemma 4.2 (Totality of Fusion). The fuse function is total.
Lemma 4.3 (Idempotence of Fusion). For all e : exp:
fuse e = fuse (fuse e)
Lemma 4.4 (Closed Expression Valuability). For all e : exp, if vars e = [], then for all
env : environ, we have that eval (env ,e) is valuable.
Lemma 4.5 (Environment Independence of Closed Expressions). For all e : exp, if vars e =
[], then for all env : environ, we have that eval (env ,e) = eval ([],e).3
2This is just one of many possible optimizations! For example, you could consider a similar optimization for
addition, or optimizing expressions like Add (Add (x,x),x) to Mul (Int 3,x). We will only consider the
given optimization for constant multiplication on multiplication in this problem, but feel free to experiment with
coding (and proving) other optimizations.3Note that this is a special case of a stronger lemma. Namely, given e : exp, if env and env ’ bind all variables
in e to the same integers and satisfy the REQUIRES of eval, then eval (env ,e) = eval (env ’,e).

Task 4.2. (1 point)

5 Probabilitrees
Probability is often confusing and unintuitive (the Monty Hall problem is a great example). To
help us better understand probability, we can draw out probability trees. Probability trees are tree
diagrams where each node represents a collection of outcomes, each leaf represents an outcome, and
each branch represents the probability that an outcome in a subtree will occur.
We have two types of probability trees: local and cumulative.
In a local probability tree, we only consider the probability of going down one branch’s subtree
as opposed to another (i.e., the probability of going left or right). Hence, a local probability tree
stores the probability of going down the left subtree or going down the right subtree.
Let’s say we wanted to model flipping a coin, and then flipping another coin if the first coin was
heads. Here’s an example of a local probability tree representing this:
•
•
"HH"
1/2
"HT"
1/2
1/2
"T"
1/2
Each dot represents a node, which has two lines, or branches, coming out of it. For our purposes,
we only consider probability trees where there are two possibilities at each node. We label the
probability of going down a branch with a rational number. At the bottom of the tree are outcomes,
which are just strings.
Something to note is that the probability that the outcome “HH” occurs is NOT 1
2 ,
but rather 1
4 . In a local probability tree, the probability of the outcome is the product of all
branches along the path from the root to the outcome. So, from the root, to get to “HH” we take
the left branch, and then another left branch, so the probability is 1
2 · 1
2 .
Now, let’s consider a cumulative probability tree for the same coin-flipping example. In a cumulative
probability tree, each branch stores the probability of going down that branch from the root of the
entire tree, rather than from the root of the local subtree. Furthermore, each outcome has a
rational number representing the probability of that outcome occurring, as well as the string
from earlier.
13
•
•
"HH", 1
4
1/4
"HT", 1
4
1/4
1/2
"T", 1
2
1/2
Notice that the numbers on the lines represent the probability of getting there from the root of
the probability tree, which is different than in the local representation! Here, the probability of an
outcome is exactly what it says.
When solving problems involving probability trees, the type of tree being used can simplify the
work done. In some cases, a local tree might be more natural, and in other cases, we would want
to use a cumulative tree.
But how do we represent probability trees in SML? Of course, it’s datatypes to the rescue! We
define:
(* A local probability tree. *)
datatype prob_local =
Outcome_Local of string
| Node_Local of (prob_local * rat) * (prob_local * rat)
(* A cumulative probability tree. *)
datatype prob_cumul =
Outcome_Cumul of string * rat
| Node_Cumul of (prob_cumul * rat) * (prob_cumul * rat)
(Note that rat is the type we will use to represent a rational number. We will elaborate on the
rat type at the end of the section.)
A probability tree is either local or cumulative. For a local probability tree, an outcome is just
a string. A node will contain two subtrees, and each subtree has a rat that represents the
probability of going down that subtree.
For a cumulative probability tree, each outcome contains a rat that represents the probability of
getting from the root to that outcome. Similarly, the rats paired with the subtrees in a node tell
the probability of arriving at the associated subtree from the root.

Task 5.1. (6 points)
First, we must make sure our probability trees are valid! A valid probability tree T should have the
following properties:
•If T is local, then for each node, the probabilities of its two subtrees should sum to 1.
•If T is cumulative, then for each node, the probabilities of its two subtrees should sum to the
probability of the node. Furthermore, the probability at an outcome should be equal to the
probability of its parent’s corresponding branch. As an edge case, if a node or outcome is at
the root of the probability tree, then the probabilities should sum to 1.
Note: We will assume that each outcome has a unique string associated. In other words, you do
not need to consider the possibility of duplicate outcomes across different branches. You can also
assume that no branch will have probability 0.

A common question that gets asked in probability is whether a particular event can happen with
high probability or low probability. Depending on who you ask, this could have different meanings.
For example, George might think an event has low probability if it has a probability less than 1
3 .

100 .

from left to right. To be specific, in the list we return, if an outcome E is in a left subtree and
outcome F is in a right subtree of a particular node, we want E to be to the left of F .
To help facilitate this, we create a new type:
type query = order * rat

5.2 Rationals
We have included a file called rationals.sml which contains helper functions to help you create
and do computations with rationals.
Note: Here, well-formed rationals are rationals that have positive denominators and there are no
common factors between the numerator and the denominator (other than 1 or −1). For example,
(1, 1), (0, 1), and (2, 3) are well-formed, but not (3, 3), (0, 10), or (4, 6).
Note: You may not need to use all the helper functions provided.

the fraction is “well-formed”)
